sql:
SELECT c.city_name, c.population_total
FROM cities c
WHERE c.population_total > (SELECT AVG(population_total) FROM cities);

external_knowledge:
- Population density is the number of people per unit area of land;
- Elevation in meters is the height above sea level;
- The year 2023 is the year of the population record.

- "Elevation type" refers to the type of elevation measurement, such as average, highest point, or lowest point;
- "Population greater than 10,000" indicates densely populated cities;
- "More than one city" ensures statistical significance in the results.

sql:
SELECT elevation_m, elevation_type, location_description
FROM elevations
WHERE elevation_type IN ('average', 'highest point') AND elevation_m > 250;

external_knowledge:
- The average elevation is calculated for cities where the elevation type is 'average';
- The average population density is calculated by dividing the total population by the land area in square miles;
- The ratio is a measure that compares the average elevation to the average population density.

- "Elderly residents" refer to people aged 65 and above;
- "Green space" includes parks, forests, and other natural areas within the city;
- "Elevation" is the height above sea level, which can vary depending on the specific measurement point (e.g., average, highest point, lowest point).

- "peaks of mountains that rose from the earth after the dawn of the 19th century" refers to cities established after the year 1800;
- "stand tall with more than one recorded height" means cities that have more than one elevation record;
- "average heights" refers to the average elevation in meters;
- "population densities" refers to the average population density (people per square mile).

- "bustling cities" refers to cities with a high population density;
- "crowd is so dense that more than 2000 people squeeze into each square mile" refers to a population density greater than 2000 people per square mile;
- "city itself stretches over more than 5 square miles" refers to a total area greater than 5 square miles.

- 'Significant water area' refers to a city with more than 2% of its area as water;
- 'Substantial green spaces' refers to an average area of green spaces greater than 10 square miles;
- 'Quite populous' refers to a city with a total population greater than 20,000.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM cities 
WHERE median_age > 0;

SELECT AVG(elevation_m) AS average_elevation, elevation_type
FROM elevations
GROUP BY elevation_type;

external_knowledge:
- "Notable elevation" implies an average elevation above 0 meters;
- "Significant population" implies a total population greater than 20,000;
- "Considerable land area" implies a land area greater than 5 square miles;
- "Small water area percentage" implies a water area percentage less than 10%.

- "Average elevation" refers to the mean elevation of the city in meters;
- "Total area" includes both land and water areas of the city in square miles;
- "Top 10" means the cities ranked in the top 10 positions.

- "Highest point" and "average" refer to types of elevation data collected for cities;
- "Population growth rate" is calculated as the percentage change in population from one year to the next;
- "Total green space" is the sum of all green spaces (parks, forests) within a city.

- "Height above sea level" refers to the average elevation in meters;
- "Number of inhabitants" refers to the average population total;
- "Land occupied" refers to the average area in square miles;
- "Year of birth" refers to the established date of the city.

- "Complete records" refer to cities that have no missing data in the selected columns, including population, area, and elevation details;
- "Demographics" include total population, gender distribution, and age distribution;
- "Area" includes total area, land area, water area, and green space area;
- "Elevation" includes elevation in meters and feet, and elevation type.
